Example : Coins detection¶

Setup¶

from PIL import Image
import numpy as np
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
from matplotlib import cm
from scipy import ndimage

%matplotlib nbagg

Open the file¶

im = Image.open('_data/coins.jpg')
channels = im.split()
r = np.array(channels[0])

Plot the histogram¶

A histogram represents the distribution of the pixels population according to their value or lightness. We can distinguish two population of pixels on the histogram, the desk and the coins.

fig = plt.figure("Rupees on the desk")
plt.clf()
fig.add_subplot(2, 1, 1)
plt.imshow(r, origin = "upper", cmap = cm.gray)
fig.add_subplot(2, 1, 2)
plt.ylabel('Number of pixels')
plt.xlabel('Values')
plt.hist(r.flatten(), bins=1000, histtype = "stepfilled")

plt.annotate('Desk', xy=(20, 60000), xytext=(50, 60000),
            arrowprops=dict(facecolor='black', shrink=0.05))
plt.annotate('Rupees', xy=(180, 10000), xytext=(180, 60000),
            arrowprops=dict(facecolor='black', shrink=0.05))
plt.grid()
plt.show()

<IPython.core.display.Javascript object>

Thresholding¶

From the red channel, thresholding is used to create a binary image composed by 0 and 1. Now the desk is represented by zeros and coins by ones.

thres = 80.
imt = r > thres

fig = plt.figure("Thresholding")
plt.imshow(imt, origin = "upper", cmap = cm.gray)
plt.colorbar()
plt.show()

<IPython.core.display.Javascript object>

Erosion and labeling¶

erod = ndimage.morphology.binary_erosion(imt, structure=np.ones((10,10)))
lab, number = ndimage.measurements.label(erod) # On compte les zones
lab = np.where(lab == 0, np.nan, lab)

fig = plt.figure("Region labeling")
plt.imshow(lab, origin = "upper", cmap = cm.jet)
plt.colorbar()
plt.show()

print ("I have",number,"coins on my desk")

<IPython.core.display.Javascript object>

I have 7 coins on my desk

Edge detection with the Sobel Filter¶

sobx = ndimage.sobel(erod, axis=0, mode='constant')
soby = ndimage.sobel(erod, axis=1, mode='constant')
sob = np.hypot(sobx, soby)

fig = plt.figure("Sobel–Feldman operator")
plt.imshow(np.where(sob > 0 , np.nan, r), origin = "upper")
plt.xlim((560, 1020))
plt.ylim((160, 650))
plt.show()

<IPython.core.display.Javascript object>

Centers of the coins¶

fig = plt.figure("Centers")
plt.imshow(r, origin = "upper")

for i in range(1,8):
    x,y= np.nonzero(np.where(lab==i,1,0))
    xmean=x.mean()
    ymean=y.mean()
    plt.plot(ymean,xmean,"w+", markersize=60)

plt.show()
